{% extends "@core/docs/_layout.twig" %}

{% block doc_content %}
<h1>Database</h1>
<p>
    Rhapsody provides a lightweight PDO wrapper with support for multiple database drivers
    and query logging for debugging.
</p>

<h2>Configuration</h2>
<p>
    Configure your database connection in the <code>.env</code> file:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-bash">DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=3306
DB_NAME=your_database
DB_USER=your_username
DB_PASS=your_password
DB_DRIVER="mysql" # mysql, pgsql, sqlite, or sqlsrv</code></pre>

<h2>Supported Drivers</h2>
<ul>
    <li><strong>MySQL</strong> – Default driver</li>
    <li><strong>PostgreSQL</strong> (<code>pgsql</code>)</li>
    <li><strong>SQLite</strong> – Use <code>:memory:</code> for in-memory testing</li>
    <li><strong>SQL Server</strong> (<code>sqlsrv</code>)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Using the Database</h2>
<p>
    The <code>Database</code> class is a singleton that lazily connects to the database
    on first use. This means pages that don't need the database won't open a connection.
</p>
<p></p>

<div class="bg-red-200 border-l-4 border-red-700 text-red-700 p-4">
    <strong>Pro tip:</strong> It is best practice to place database queries inside models, rather than 
    in your controllers (separation of concerns). This will keep your controllers clutter-free and make 
    testing / maintaining your code much simpler. See <a href="{{ base_url }}/docs/models">models documentation</a> 
    for more information.
</div>

<h3>Getting a Connection</h3>
<pre><code class="language-php">use Rhapsody\Core\Database;

// Get the global instance
$db = Database::getInstance($config);
$pdo = $db->getConnection();

// Execute a query
$stmt = $pdo->query("SELECT * FROM users WHERE id = 1");
$user = $stmt->fetch();</code></pre>

<h3>Prepared Statements</h3>
<pre><code class="language-php">$pdo = Database::getInstance($config)->getConnection();
$stmt = $pdo->prepare("SELECT * FROM users WHERE email = :email");
$stmt->execute([':email' => 'user@example.com']);
$user = $stmt->fetch();</code></pre>

<h2>Query Logging</h2>
<p>
    The <code>TraceablePDO</code> class extends the native PDO and logs all queries
    for debugging purposes. The debug toolbar displays these logs in the <strong>Database</strong> panel.
</p>
<p>
    To access the query log programmatically:
</p>
<pre><code class="language-php">$queries = TraceablePDO::getQueryLog();
foreach ($queries as $query) {
    echo $query['sql'] . ' (' . $query['executionMS'] . 'ms)';
}</code></pre>

<h2>N+1 Query Detection</h2>
<p>
    The debug toolbar automatically detects and warns about N+1 query patterns
    when the same query is executed multiple times.
</p>
{% endblock %}